<div id="peerReviewProcess"><hr style="border: 2px solid gray;">
<h3>Peer Review Process&nbsp;</h3>
<p><strong>Article Review Process</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1</strong>: When a manuscript is received, it is first submitted to examination with the&nbsp;<em>Turnitin</em>&nbsp;program to detect possible plagiarism or self-plagiarism. Subsequently, the editorial board reviews the manuscript before submitting it to peer-review. Depending on the outcome, the manuscript may be either rejected or pre-accepted. Pre-accepted manuscripts are then sent over to two double blind reviewers who are given a month to submit their final evaluation of the manuscript.</p>
<p>The peer reviewers are chosen according to criteria established by international bibliographic databases and indexes.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2</strong>: If the results of both evaluations from the reviewers are positive and do not involve changes, the manuscript is accepted for publication. If evaluations are positive, but the reviewers suggest changes, the manuscripts and the reviewers’ comments are sent back to the author(s) to make the corresponding changes. If the evaluations are negative, the manuscript is rejected. If there is a disparity between evaluations, one being positive and the other negative, the manuscript is submitted to a third peer-reviewer.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3</strong>: Once a unanimous decision regarding the submitted manuscript has been reached, the last comments and suggestions are forwarded to the author(s) who will have one month to submit a final edited version. When the second version of the manuscript is received, it is sent back to the peer reviewers to issue a final judgement on the status of the paper. If evaluations are negative, the manuscript is rejected. Otherwise, the manuscript is accepted for publication.&nbsp;</p>
</div>
